Nairobi county outshone its peers in revenue collection in the last financial year according to the latest report by Controller of Budget Agnes Odhiambo. The report also shows that the county posted a significant decrease in the expenditure on local and foreign travel and allowances by the executive and MCAs. The Annual County Governments Budget Implementation Review Report for the 2017-18 financial year indicates that City Hall collected the highest amount – Sh10.1 billion during the year. The collection was however a Sh7.5 per cent decrease compared to10.9 billion generated in 2016-17. The revenue realised was also only 58.7 per cent of the annual internal revenue target. The money was generated from land rates, advertising, parking, single business permits and building approval and other resources. Nairobi was followed by Mombasa and Nakuru at Sh3.1 billion and Sh2.2 billion respectively. Narok generated Sh2.1 billion, Kiambu – Sh1.6 billion and Machakos raked in Sh1 billion from its internal revenue sources. Lamu, Tana River and Mandera counties collected the lowest amount at 55.2 million, Sh55.6 million and Sh61.8 million respectively. In total, all the 47 devolved units collected Sh32.4 billion from their internal sources against the target of Sh49.2 billion during the year. According to the report, Nairobi spent Sh476.9 million on domestic travel – comprising Sh198.5 million by MCAs and Sh278.4 million by the executive during the year. The expenditure represented a 6.2 per cent reduction on travels compared to Sh639.3 million spent the year before. The report also shows that the county registered a 16 per cent decrease in the expenditure on sitting allowances to its 128 MCAs. It spent Sh73.9 million on the sitting allowances of the ward reps against the budget allocation of Sh112.4 million. This was a decreased compare to Sh88 million spent in the 20160-17 financial year. It indicates that on average, monthly sitting allowance was Sh48,130 per MCA compared to Salary and Remuneration Commission's monthly ceiling of Sh80,000. Odhiambo raised a red flag in her report on the huge expenditure on personal emoluments which include salaries, allowances, local and foreign travel. All the county governments, according to the report, spent an aggregate of Sh151 billion on personal emoluments, a 15.4 per cent increase compared to the 2016-17 financial year. Click here for the latest political news